segments.text: I said, I want to live in the back of my pickup truck.
And I have a camper, and I've got a little bed in there, and I've got a little cooler that I put ice in.
And I said, you know, I can shower and shave at the handball courts because I was playing handball every chance I got.
And he said, well, you can't be in B1.
He says, if you're not in the barracks, you can't be in B1.
So he says, I'll go talk to Colonel Baker, but you'll have to go into the H1.
I said, sir, that's a married company.
He says, well, you'll be the only bachelor in the married company then.
And he says, the only other thing you've got to do is you've got to go get written permission from the campus security.
Because when I go to Colonel Baker, I want it to be OK.
And so I went, and the campus security was in the OYMCA, down in the basement to the right.
And there was three people in the campus security.
You know, I mean, there may have been four or five, but there was never more than three policemen there.
And I went in there and I said, look, this is, and I laid out my plan.
Well, I know they knew that this was not going to last.
There's no way, you know, anybody would stay in a pickup truck forever in the camper.
But, you know, they checked, and I had never had one, no parking tickets.
I had not had one incident on the campus.
And I told them I was working with my advisor, and I was in the Corps and everything.
So he wrote out a handwritten little note, and I took it up to Captain Simmons.
And he said, where do you want to stay?
Where are you going to park this thing?
And I said, well, I'd like to park it in the same place.
And they said, well, and so we talked about it.
And I don't know if he suggested or I suggested, but there was an oak tree behind Guyon Hall that provided good shade.
And so I kind of, for some reason, would always get that parking lot, parking spot.
But I parked in Guyon Hall.
I showered and shaved when I was here at the handball courts.
And I studied at the library.
And you were taking a full course load.
Oh, yeah.
And I was in the core.
And nobody came by and rattled the pickup?
No, the only thing that would...
It was kind of interesting.
One January, maybe in January of 67, I don't know, I had...
I usually face the truck to the north, but that, for some reason, I faced the truck to the south.
I guess I had a different parking space.
And an ice storm came up, and it was a world-class ice storm.
And my pickup, to get out of my camper, above the pickup, you just open the top, and then you had to open that, and you jumped out.
I mean, it didn't have a door.
It just had an opening.
Well, it was iced shut.
And I'm sitting there kicking on it, you know, trying to get out because I got to go to class.
And somebody came by and said, there's somebody in the back of that truck.
And I hollered at them.
And so they got something hard and chipped the ice and I got out.
And then sometimes the parking lot would be filling.
And what would happen, I'd go to the farm and I'd work

especially in the spring, till, you know, dark, 8 or 9 o'clock, and then I'd come, and instead of spending the night, if I had an 8 o'clock class, and I'd come back, and it'd be 10 or 11 o'clock by the time I'd get in, I'd go right to bed, and then I'd set the alarm.
Well, people would hear the alarm go off sometime, and I'd hear them say, I heard an alarm, and then, you know, you would meet.
And my bed, you couldn't sit up in my bed.
you had to roll out of bed.
If you sat up, you hit your head.
And then, you know, you were on your knees, and so I had a cushion in there with a carpet.
And then, you know, I kept my uniforms in there and put my Aggie boots on every day and pulled them off by myself and shined them.
Now, you ate at Dunkin'?
Well, no.
Once I stopped rooming board, I ate at the Kettle.
which was on Highway 6, which is now a donut shop across from Luby's.
But it was called The Kettle, and I ate all my meals there, and they had a blackboard off to the side, and everybody knew
that that's where I ate, and that was my message board.

People would come in and write me a message and say, because we didn't have cell phones, I didn't have a phone, I didn't have a phone at the ranch, and they could wait around, they knew where I parked, but they would write me notes.
And so when I ate, I ate at the kettle, and I knew everybody in there, and that was my message board for a year and a half.
Now, as we're heading toward commencement now, how important was final review as a junior?
And then what was it like for a senior?
Well.
What was it like to wear those senior boots officially for the first time?
Yeah, I, you know, that's a good question.
and let me see, that would have been in 67, that would have been in May of 67.
Let me see if I can find an entry in, yeah, it had been, or May of 66, it had been May of 66.
The year before you graduated.
Yeah, and then I, well, see, because I graduated in January of 68, but I was class of 67, so I'll,
It would have been May of 66.
I guess.
Let's see if I even wrote anything down.
May 3rd.
Juniors are on rotation now to morning chow, but I intend to...
Jumped.
Woke up at daylight.
I always seem to wake up at daylight.
Uh...
Economics 204, still, today's another good day.
Should have been a Saturday.
Yeah, okay, Saturday the 21st.
No, I went to a swimming meet on Saturday the 21st.
My little sister was an Olympic swimmer, and she was an unbelievable swimmer, and when swimming meets were close by, I'd go watch her swim.
She was the finest athlete.
When would...

very hot saturday the 28th of may final review saturday 28th of may cloudy and very hot woke up at six and ronnie thomas by then was my roommate and he was on the golf team and i went to the kettle and ate breakfast took bull tech's quiz at seven it was very long and tedious but not hard went over to gary moon's to play guitars till
noon and then took him out to eat at Kittle.
Came back and got ready for final review.
Folks arrived late but
Everything is okay.
Daddy took pictures.
It was real hot, but it's great to be a senior.
My boots fit and looked fabulous.
We went out to eat after the review, and the folks went to the farm and took Jeannie.
I'm here at the dorm.
Just took a shower.
Final review, 1966.
Summer camp.
flight training, graduation, helicopter pilot.
For some reason, I decided to put all that at the end, but I didn't go into too much about that final review.
All right, now then, what was it like as a senior?
How did you feel in that final review and commencement?
Yeah, well, let me, the commencement, because I graduated
Oh, that's right.
See, in January of 68, it was not the same.
It was because I knew I had another semester of school.
But graduation and commissioning ceremony, Saturday the 20th of January of 68.
I parked my truck on the street next to the handball court so I would have a good parking place.
At 4 a.m., the street cleaner woke me up.
And it was much like Christmas Day when I was a child.
I could not go back to sleep, even though I had only been asleep for three hours.
At six, I went to the dorm, showered and dressed in Aggie senior uniform.
At eight, I filled out papers and was sworn in by Colonel Blake.
At 10 o'clock graduation began and lasted until noon, General Rutter talked too long.
And one of the things, I've given lots and lots of speeches.
My speeches are all short.
And I gave the commissioning speech here in May last year, and it was nine minutes long.
I said, look, just tell me how long it is.
And it was nine minutes.
And I got the Board of Regents.
I got six letters from the Board of Regents.
They said they'd never had a nine-minute speech before.
And I said, you know, you don't have to have a good speech if it's short.
I saw Jeannie and Marilyn, that's my sister, for just a few minutes because I had to change into my army greens for commissioning.
Commissioning was a very impressive ceremony.
General James K. Woolnock, Woolnock,
Kornark Commander, four-star, gave me my commission, which I had to give back because it was a reserve and not a regular commission.
They'd made a mistake because I was commissioned as a regular officer.
Jeannie and Marilyn pinned my bars on.
My mama and daddy had the flu and were very sick and didn't come.
I was saluted and gave away a dollar bill, which, you know, is a tradition.
And...
told everybody goodbye and drove to Fort Benning, Georgia.
So I was commissioned, graduated, and left for Fort Benning on January the 20th.
How well prepared did you believe A&M had made you?
How well prepared were you for what you thought was your future?
Well, yeah, at that time.
What I think A&M did was, and it may have been ROTC summer camp, tied in, but I was confident, but never overconfident.
I finished all my Army schools, either the honor graduate or in the top 1% or 2%.
None of them were hard.
Went to airborne school, and I remember

I went to airborne school after ranger school and the airborne school sergeants were black hats and they thought they were mean and tough and this one sergeant is yelling at me and I'm a second lieutenant and I've been through OBC and ranger school and I was an honor graduate from ranger school.
And an airborne school physically is a piece of cake compared to ranger school.
And I was in superb condition, always was.
And this sergeant's yelling at me about something.
And he finally asked me a question or something or allowed me to speak.
And I said, Sarge, I hate to tell you this, but you're a rookie compared to an Aggie pisshead.
And he had no clue what I was talking about, but he knew that it was not favorable.
And he got so mad, and he just stormed off and everything.
But, you know, no, I think the Aggie program and the experience...
You know, just plus my raising.
I mean, I was raised in the woods.
I was raised by a grand... You know, my grandfather just spent a tremendous amount of time with me.
And I was always very confident of my ability to do physical hand-eye coordination.
I mean, anything like that.
I mean, you know, if I went into a GRE exam, I wasn't ever confident.
But if I was having to do something where...
your wits depended upon it or your calmness or your decision-making or your ability to accomplish or overcome an obstacle.
I was just confident without being overconfident.
Did A&M help to build that confidence?
Well, I think it was the whole program.
I was very gifted to have a wonderful family that kind of...
you know, kind of continued along with A&M.
And then I think A&M just because of...
of all the experiences and the traditions that you put in in such an important period of your life.
And it was very disciplined.
I mean, A&M was a very disciplined place, and I liked that.
And so I think it just fit very well for me.
It was one of those things, like I tell folks, the Army's not for everybody, but for some people it's perfect.
And A&M's not for everybody, but for some people it's just perfect.
And it was...
I was a...
I was a rebel without being a troublemaker.
I wasn't a follower.
I would not just do things because I thought through things.
And A&M, the whole experience lets you figure all that out for yourself.
This Aggie spirit that all of us refer to, what is it, what makes it, and why is it important?
I saw that...
in your paper and I've been thinking about it because I've read where some very gifted people have written some really neat things about what the Aggie spirit means to them.
What it means to me is things like, is the personal,

aspects of things happening like silver taps where my brother's not an Aggie and he comes and it's his son and he's in an unbelievable grieving state and there's something occurs at 8 a.m. that doesn't occur any place else in the world and he is a non-Aggie, feels it and to this day you know just it's he talks about it every once in a while he'll never forget it
It's just all the experiences I get with Bear Pickivance, who's coming here in September and is a great friend.
He's worked for me twice.
I've known him since 1964.
Every once in a while, we would be wrestling with a very difficult issue in the Pacific Ocean that was political, hot potato.
soldier, sailor, airman, Marines lives at stake.
I mean, some tough issues.
And he would grin at me and he says, you know, if two Aggies can't figure this out, it can't be figured out.
And it would kind of break the ice, you know, and it was just, you know, and Pat Gamble was the PACAF commander at the time.
And a couple of times we were in some tough meetings.

And there would be a break and there'd be friction and everything else and Bear and Pat and I would just kind of get together in a car and he says, you know, if three Aggies can't figure this out, it can't be figured out.
And we'd go back into this meeting and solve what would be a problem for the President of the United States or the Secretary of Defense or the Secretary of State and we would solve it.
And so I think the Aggie spirit is just experiences
where you had personal situations happen and it just permeates.
You can't describe it.
You can't necessarily put your finger on it.
It's like a lot of things.
You know it when you see it.
You feel it.
Is one of the keys that it's inclusive?
instead of exclusive meaning it doesn't matter about your family's accent.
Oh yeah, right.
No, because the

You know, I was at a big meeting last Thursday in San Antonio, and this, you know, I was representing this group and everything, and this guy who we were meeting with who was Hispanic, he says, is that an Aggie ring?
And I said, yes, it is.
And he said, what class?
I said, 67.
And he said, 74.
And we saw, and from then on,
it was just wrapping up the meeting, you know.
And has this spirit meant much to you in your life, you think?
Well, yeah, I've always been proud of being an Aggie.
And like during Vietnam, the Aggies, there was no, to my knowledge, there was no, I mean, I've,
I've read a lot.
I've read Vannevar's book on Johnson wars, and I've read a lot about the decision making for Vietnam.
And if I were king and could relive it again, we wouldn't have gotten involved.
But we were involved.
Soldiers were dying.
Other schools in the Southwest Conference were picketing, were having demonstrations.
And if you were in ROTC at Texas University, you couldn't wear your uniform out of the ROTC building there at Texas.
None of that happened at A&M.
When Clinton talks about how he agonized over the Vietnam War, and that was part of his decision-making on some of the decisions he made,
Coming from A&M, with the traditions of the Aggies, whether or not it was a just war, it was America's war, and Aggies were going to go do their duty to God and country.
They weren't going to have these intellectual...
you know, debates on things, at least at the time.
I mean, there's a time for debating and there's a time for action.
And I was always proud of A&M, you know, just because it seemed to have been able to sort through those things.
And then subsequently has done some great analysis and some great work.
And, you know, and as I think all of us, you know, would say, you know,

you know may have been something that we didn't need you know communism could have fallen Soviet Union could have fallen probably without Vietnam we'll never know but no the whole everything I've always been very proud to be an Aggie and when Jeannie decided to come back to College Station or come to College Station to live I just thought it was a wonderful fit to be able to come home because there's a comfort
There's a comfort level in this part of Texas.
So you think A&M has been a significant factor in your life?
Yeah.
There's just no doubt about it.
I was just turned 18 when I got here.
and I left at just turning 22.
So it's that formative stages of your life, and a lot of bad things can happen.
Because there was a lot of bad things happening at other universities, and they just weren't happening here.
There was still...
you know, a very doing things right, honorable.
All those things were things that meant something.
All right.
Now the consultant question.
You've just been selected as a consultant to A&M's leadership regarding the future of A&M.
What advice would you give A&M to do and or not to do?
Uh...
I've given five speeches at A&M in the last 10 years.
And in all five of them, I'm not sure if they have been positively received by everyone, but I have gotten letters back from many.
And what I tell people is you have to watch the balance of things.
And it's just like trying to make the bonfire bigger every year.
I don't think that's a balanced way of looking at things.
I've been a real proponent of the Parsons Cavalry.
I'm an equestrian.
I've really loved what they've done.
But when they were running off all their women,
Well, the equestrian term is a seat.
Does that person have a good seat?
Women are the finest riders there are.
My little sister is the finest equestrian I know.
But they had a rites of passage out there where they had to chew tobacco.
Well, that ran off a bunch of women, and they lost a bunch of wonderful equestrians.
So I tell the Aggies, I said,
You know, your strength also sometimes is your weakness.
Our strength is our weakness.
Our strength is our zealous love of the school.
It's also our weakness.
And we've got to balance life, and you have to balance your family, your God, your profession, your school, and you've got to keep things in balance.
And you just can't...
You know, we've got liberals and we've got conservatives, but have you ever heard of a plane flying with only one wing?
Planes fly because they have two wings.
And as life is tough out there, and the folks that I've seen that have made the greatest contributions to our society
There was a fervor about them, but there was a balance in their life.
And I said, you know, that would be my counsel.
Yes, darling.
Okay, right.
We've got to go to a dinner party here in a little while.
We're about through.
We're within ten minutes.
We're about through.
If you'll just lay out my cloak.

Okay, if you could make a major gift, somebody walks up and hands you a check for a million dollars, but the stipulation is you must pass it on to A&M, but you decide the use of the money, what would you want A&M to do with a major gift if you were the decision maker?
Well, because I have been in programatics, especially the last 15 years, where I've managed

large amount of money uh... i have some strong feelings about that and what i would do is is i would give it to the president to use as he saw fit what happens to us in this world is we're provided the congress gives department of defense monies but says generals this is where you will spend it
You will build these ships in my district, and you will do this, and you will do that.
And so the discretionary funds that the leadership has at the senior levels is very limited because you get all this fenced money.
Well, when I watch what's happening at A&M, and I think of, and I know Ray Bowen, and I greatly respect him, and I'm sure that I'll respect the next president, to me what he needs...
is the latitude to make decisions, and he's got a lot of help.
He's got a lot of people to look over his shoulder.
So if I was going to give an endowment, I would go to the president and say, you know, where do you need this money?
Where is there a need?
Because it may be
you know, the Sterling Library has enough.
It may be that this program has enough, and if you fenced it, that wouldn't help him.

And so I think because I've had, I've been at the end of a lot of fenced money where I, as a leader, knew where I needed it, and I couldn't because of legislation or other regulations put it there, I would want it unfeathered, you know, to where...
where the leader could, at the time, the guy that's responsible could put it to the best use.
Are there some A&M related people to whom you feel deep personal debts of gratitude?
Well, I've referred several times to this captain and now Lieutenant Colonel Jim Simmons, who is still a wonderful friend.
And when he finished his career in the military, he, for 20-plus years now, has been teaching junior ROTC at St. Joe, Missouri.
And he promoted me to major.
He was at my brigadier general's ceremony.
promotion ceremony.
And there was a couple of times where I went to him and he really gave me wonderful advice.
And sage advice.
He didn't give me the party line.
He figured out that I was an individual who was a little different than other people.
And I felt always took that difference into consideration and tried to put a positive spin on it.
I'm not sure what would have, a couple of times, which way I would have gone, you know, because it was a great disappointment when I did not get in vet school.
I mean, if your whole life all you want to do is be a vet, you don't want to be an engineer, you don't want to be a doctor, you just want to be a horse doctor.
And then all of a sudden the cards are there and you're not going to be a vet, at least not in the near term.
You know, and Jim Simmons, Captain, later Lieutenant Colonel Jim Simmons, was a great friend and confidant and someone that I could go to.
And I'm the kind of guy that just doesn't bear my soul, you know, wouldn't bear my soul to many people.
I mean, I saw most of the...
you know, most of the problems I solved myself, you know, and I, and so I didn't seek a lot of counsel.
I thought Dr. Romaine gave me good counsel.

Uh, and, uh, and then, uh, and later Dr. Wooten, uh, matter of fact, Dr. Wooten helped me get a very good summer job the summer of 67 in the crop reporting service that really was, was a, was a very helpful to me.
And he orchestrated that.
And, and, um,
You know, and what I always, what I try to do is it is easy to take care and take interest in the superstars and to do the disciplinary things you have to do with the troublemakers.
But there's a huge mass in the middle that doesn't cause any problems and a lot of them are late bloomers.
And a lot of them are just there.
And what I try to do as an Army officer was to focus on that group in the middle and to coach, teach, and mentor and try to, because the superstars are gonna make it without any help.
The troublemakers, you're gonna discipline according to the Uniform Code of Military Justice or what are the rules and regulations.
But where you really build the great teams of teams is in the middle.
And I think because I was in the middle and because some of these guys figured that out and gave me good counsel, it provided the role models for me for 33 years to kind of do the same.
Have we left any topics out that we should have covered?
Let me just check my notes right quick.
Because I've only got one question left.
Okay, sir.
I told athlete Randy Mattson, no bonfire.
Wall Street Journal, security concussions.
Oh, I had a third concussion of my fourth was that
as a fish playing hall hockey, and hall hockey was illegal.
And I was knocked cold on the radiator in dorm 17.
And when I woke up in the clinic, one of my upper class
